
[1]rehearse

   REHEARSE, v.t. rehers.'

   1. To recite; to repeat the words of a passage or composition; to
   repeat the words of another.

   When the words were heard which David spoke, they rehearsed them before
   Saul. 1Sam. 17.

   2. To narrate or recount events or transactions.

   There shall they rehearse the righteous acts of the Lord. Judges 5.
   Acts 11.

   3. To recite or repeat in private for experiment and improvement,
   before a public representation; as, to rehearse a tragedy.
